Test technique (12/06/2023)¶

Smart grid¶

1. Problem¶

  • Develop a distribution algorithm of an energy management system (EMS)
  • Design architecture and algorithms

2. Problem translation and suggested solution¶

3. Object-oriented design¶

  • Four "instantiable" classes :
    • EnergyStorageSystem
    • IndustrialSite
    • PhotovoltaicPowerPlant
    • PointOfConnection
  • One static class :
    • Grid
  • Provide utility functions and documentation for measures unit
    • kW -> kWh (stock vs. flow)
    • W -> kW
    • Documenting and provide hints

4. Best practices¶

  • Testing (TDD-like, unit-tests)
  • Virtual environment to manage dependencies and package code base (poetry)
  • Formatting (pep8) : enforcing naming conventions and style
  • Numpy-style code documentation

5. Project management¶

  • Git/GitHub : gitflow
  • Naming conventions for git "verbs" (["ADD"], ["MOD"], etc.)

6. Limitations and further elements¶

  • Python : used as a prototyping language (loose typing, performance issues)
  • Performances bottleneck (a lot of writting, reading operations)
    • Heavy and critical real-time running application (update states often)
  • Static typing and stability (performances, project management)
  • Suggesting statically typed language supporting effective and quick read/write operations (required to reflect on time complexity of our solution, use hash-maps data structures for O(1))
